    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1935-04-18T12:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1935-04-18T12:00:00-05:00" n="325"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d325">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">462.00R296/5912: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Dodd</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Berlin</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1935-04-18T18:00:00+01:00"
                            >April 18, 1935—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received April 18—2:25 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>83. Department’s instruction No. 31, April 17, 7 p.m. Foreign Office promised
                    reply in a few days to verbatim <hi rend="italic">aide-mémoire</hi> presented
                    today. In interview it was stated that juridically speaking there was no
                    justification of apparent discrimination but that special and clearing
                    arrangements between Germany and other countries insuring full payment resulted
                    from action of those countries and is not controllable by Germany, and that
                    while regretting the situation Germany cannot pay otherwise.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Dodd</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
